HEADWORD: Patriarchate
<hw>Pa`tri*ar"chate</hw> <pr>(p⟦amac⟧`tr⟦icr⟧*⟦aum⟧r"k⟦asl⟧t)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>patriarcat</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The office, dignity, or jurisdiction of a patriarch.</def>
<rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The residence of an ecclesiastic
patriarch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>A patriarchal form of
government or society. See <er>Patriarchal</er>, <pos>a.</pos>,
3.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patriarchdom</ent>⟦br⟧
